Note:
compiler/frontend/primitives/types/validation.runa
Type Validation Primitives

This module provides fundamental type validation operations for all Runa primitive types.

Key features and capabilities:
- Type checking and validation for all primitive types
- Range validation for numeric types
- Format validation for strings and identifiers
- Constraint validation with custom rules
- Type compatibility checking
- Schema validation for structured data
- Performance-optimized validation routines
- Zero-allocation validation where possible
- Integration with compiler type system
- Comprehensive error reporting
- Thread-safe validation operations
- Locale-aware validation rules
:End Note

Import "dev/debug/errors/core" as Errors
Import "text/core/regex" as Regex
Import "text/core/pattern_matching" as PatternMatch
Import "text/string/core" as StringCore

Note: =====================================================================
Note: VALIDATION RESULT TYPES
Note: =====================================================================

Type called "ValidationResult":
    is_valid as Boolean                        Note: Whether validation passed
    error_code as Optional[String]             Note: Error code for failed validation
    error_message as Optional[String]          Note: Human-readable error description
    field_name as Optional[String]             Note: Name of field that failed validation
    expected_value as Optional[String]         Note: What was expected
    actual_value as Optional[String]           Note: What was actually provided

Type called "ValidationRule":
    rule_name as String                        Note: Identifier for the validation rule
    rule_type as String                        Note: Type of validation (range, format, custom)
    parameters as Dictionary[String, String]   Note: Rule-specific parameters
    error_message as String                    Note: Custom error message for this rule
    is_required as Boolean                     Note: Whether this rule is mandatory


Type called "ValidationContext":
    field_path as List[String]                 Note: Path to current field being validated
    parent_type as Optional[String]            Note: Type of parent object
    validation_mode as String                  Note: Strict, lenient, or custom mode
    locale_settings as Dictionary[String, String] Note: Locale-specific validation settings

Note: =====================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "validate_wildcard_pattern" that takes value as String, pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Validate string against wildcard pattern (* and ? wildcards)
    Note: * matches zero or more characters, ? matches exactly one character
    Note: Supports basic glob-style pattern matching
    
    Let value_pos be 0
    Let pattern_pos be 0
    Let value_len be length of value
    Let pattern_len be length of pattern
    
    Note: Track star matching state for backtracking
    Let star_value_pos be -1
    Let star_pattern_pos be -1
    
    Note: Main matching loop
    Loop while value_pos is less than value_len:
        Let pattern_char be ""
        Let value_char be character at position value_pos in value
        
        Note: Get current pattern character if available
        If pattern_pos is less than pattern_len:
            Let pattern_char be character at position pattern_pos in pattern
        
        Note: Handle different pattern characters
        If pattern_pos is less than pattern_len And (pattern_char equals value_char Or pattern_char equals "?"):
            Note: Direct match or single character wildcard
            Let value_pos be value_pos plus 1
            Let pattern_pos be pattern_pos plus 1
        Otherwise If pattern_pos is less than pattern_len And pattern_char equals "*":
            Note: Star wildcard - save positions for backtracking
            Let star_pattern_pos be pattern_pos
            Let star_value_pos be value_pos
            Let pattern_pos be pattern_pos plus 1
        Otherwise If star_pattern_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
            Note: Backtrack to star position and try next character
            Let pattern_pos be star_pattern_pos plus 1
            Let star_value_pos be star_value_pos plus 1
            Let value_pos be star_value_pos
        Otherwise:
            Note: No match and no star to backtrack to
            Return false
    
    Note: Handle remaining pattern characters (should only be stars)
    Loop while pattern_pos is less than pattern_len:
        Let pattern_char be character at position pattern_pos in pattern
        If not (pattern_char equals "*"):
            Return false
        Let pattern_pos be pattern_pos plus 1
    
    Note: Successfully matched entire value and pattern
    Return true

Process called "get_character_code" that takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Get ASCII/Unicode code point for a single character
    Note: Returns the numeric code for character comparison and validation
    
    Note: Control characters (0-31)
    If char equals "\0":
        Return 0
    Otherwise If char equals "\t":
        Return 9
    Otherwise If char equals "\n":
        Return 10
    Otherwise If char equals "\r":
        Return 13
    Note: Printable ASCII characters (32-126)
    Otherwise If char equals " ":
        Return 32
    Otherwise If char equals "!":
        Return 33
    Otherwise If char equals "\"":
