Note: =====================================================================
Note: PRIMITIVE TYPE VALIDATION
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "validate_integer" that takes value as String, min_value as Optional[Integer], max_value as Optional[Integer] returns ValidationResult:
    Note: Validate string represents a valid integer within optional range
    Note: Checks for proper numeric format, leading zeros, sign handling
    Note: Validates against minimum and maximum bounds if provided
    Note: Handles edge cases like overflow, underflow, and malformed input
    
    Let result be ValidationResult with:
        is_valid as false
        error_code as null
        error_message as null
        field_name as null
        expected_value as null
        actual_value as value
    
    Note: Check for empty or null string
    If value equals "" Or value equals null:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value cannot be empty for integer validation"
        Return result
    
    Note: Remove leading and trailing whitespace
    Let trimmed_value be value
    Let start_index be 0
    Let end_index be 0
    
    Note: Find first non-whitespace character
    Loop while start_index is less than length of trimmed_value:
        Let char be character at position start_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let start_index be start_index plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Find last non-whitespace character
    Let end_index be length of trimmed_value minus 1
    Loop while end_index is greater than start_index:
        Let char be character at position end_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let end_index be end_index minus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Extract trimmed substring
    If start_index is greater than end_index:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value contains only whitespace"
        Return result
    
    Let trimmed_value be substring of trimmed_value from start_index to end_index plus 1
    
    Note: Check for sign
    Let has_sign be false
    Let is_negative be false
    Let number_start be 0
    
    If length of trimmed_value is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be character at position 0 in trimmed_value
        If first_char equals "+":
            Let has_sign be true
            Let number_start be 1
        Otherwise If first_char equals "-":
            Let has_sign be true
            Let is_negative be true
            Let number_start be 1
    
    Note: Check if we have digits after sign
    If number_start is greater than or equal to length of trimmed_value:
        Let result.error_code be "INVALID_FORMAT"
        Let result.error_message be "Sign character must be followed by digits"
        Return result
    
    Note: Validate all remaining characters are digits
    Let digit_count be 0
    Let leading_zeros be 0
    Let first_nonzero_found be false
    
    Loop with i from number_start to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
        Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
        If char equals "0" And not first_nonzero_found:
            Let leading_zeros be leading_zeros plus 1
        Otherwise If char equals "1" Or char equals "2" Or char equals "3" Or char equals "4" Or char equals "5" Or char equals "6" Or char equals "7" Or char equals "8" Or char equals "9":
            Let first_nonzero_found be true
            Let digit_count be digit_count plus 1
        Otherwise If char equals "0" And first_nonzero_found:
            Let digit_count be digit_count plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let result.error_code be "INVALID_CHARACTER"
            Let result.error_message be "Invalid character '" concatenated with char concatenated with "' in integer"
            Return result
    
    Note: Check for leading zeros (not allowed except for single "0")
    If leading_zeros is greater than 1:
        Let result.error_code be "LEADING_ZEROS"
        Let result.error_message be "Integer cannot have leading zeros"
        Return result
    
    If leading_zeros equals 1 And digit_count is greater than 0:
        Let result.error_code be "LEADING_ZEROS"
        Let result.error_message be "Integer cannot have leading zeros"
        Return result
    
    Note: Handle the special case of just "0"
    Let total_digits be leading_zeros plus digit_count
    If total_digits equals 0:
        Let result.error_code be "NO_DIGITS"
        Let result.error_message be "No digits found in integer value"
        Return result
    
    Note: Convert string to integer for range checking
    Let parsed_integer be 0
    Let multiplier be 1
    
    Note: Parse digits from right to left
    Loop with i from length of trimmed_value minus 1 down to number_start:
        Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
        Let digit_value be 0
        
        If char equals "0":
            Let digit_value be 0
        Otherwise If char equals "1":
            Let digit_value be 1
        Otherwise If char equals "2":
            Let digit_value be 2
        Otherwise If char equals "3":
            Let digit_value be 3
        Otherwise If char equals "4":
            Let digit_value be 4
        Otherwise If char equals "5":
            Let digit_value be 5
        Otherwise If char equals "6":
            Let digit_value be 6
        Otherwise If char equals "7":
            Let digit_value be 7
        Otherwise If char equals "8":
            Let digit_value be 8
        Otherwise If char equals "9":
            Let digit_value be 9
        
        Note: Check for overflow during parsing
        If multiplier is greater than 214748364:
            Let result.error_code be "OVERFLOW"
            Let result.error_message be "Integer value too large"
            Return result
        
        Let addition_result be digit_value multiplied by multiplier
        If parsed_integer is greater than 2147483647 minus addition_result:
            Let result.error_code be "OVERFLOW"
            Let result.error_message be "Integer value too large"
            Return result
        
        Let parsed_integer be parsed_integer plus addition_result
        Let multiplier be multiplier multiplied by 10
    
    Note: Apply sign
    If is_negative:
        If parsed_integer is greater than 2147483648:
            Let result.error_code be "UNDERFLOW"
            Let result.error_message be "Integer value too small"
            Return result
        Let parsed_integer be 0 minus parsed_integer
    
    Note: Validate range constraints
    If min_value is not null:
        If parsed_integer is less than min_value:
            Let result.error_code be "BELOW_MINIMUM"
            Let result.error_message be "Value " concatenated with trimmed_value concatenated with " is below minimum " concatenated with min_value
            Let result.expected_value be "value >= " concatenated with min_value
            Return result
    
    If max_value is not null:
        If parsed_integer is greater than max_value:
            Let result.error_code be "ABOVE_MAXIMUM"
            Let result.error_message be "Value " concatenated with trimmed_value concatenated with " is above maximum " concatenated with max_value
            Let result.expected_value be "value <= " concatenated with max_value
            Return result
    
    Note: Validation successful
    Let result.is_valid be true
    Return result

Process called "validate_float" that takes value as String, precision as Optional[Integer], scale as Optional[Integer] returns ValidationResult:
    Note: Validate string represents a valid floating-point number
    Note: Precision controls total digits, scale controls decimal places
    Note: Handles scientific notation, infinity, and NaN values
    Note: Validates numeric formatting and range constraints
    
    Let result be ValidationResult with:
        is_valid as false
        error_code as null
        error_message as null
        field_name as null
        expected_value as null
        actual_value as value
    
    Note: Check for empty or null string
    If value equals "" Or value equals null:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value cannot be empty for float validation"
        Return result
    
    Note: Remove leading and trailing whitespace
    Let trimmed_value be value
    Let start_index be 0
    Let end_index be 0
    
    Note: Find first non-whitespace character
    Loop while start_index is less than length of trimmed_value:
        Let char be character at position start_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let start_index be start_index plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Find last non-whitespace character
    Let end_index be length of trimmed_value minus 1
    Loop while end_index is greater than start_index:
        Let char be character at position end_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let end_index be end_index minus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Extract trimmed substring
    If start_index is greater than end_index:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value contains only whitespace"
        Return result
    
    Let trimmed_value be substring of trimmed_value from start_index to end_index plus 1
    
    Note: Check for special float values
    If trimmed_value equals "inf" Or trimmed_value equals "Inf" Or trimmed_value equals "INF" Or trimmed_value equals "infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "Infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "INFINITY":
        Let result.is_valid be true
        Return result
    
    If trimmed_value equals "-inf" Or trimmed_value equals "-Inf" Or trimmed_value equals "-INF" Or trimmed_value equals "-infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "-Infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "-INFINITY":
        Let result.is_valid be true
        Return result
    
    If trimmed_value equals "+inf" Or trimmed_value equals "+Inf" Or trimmed_value equals "+INF" Or trimmed_value equals "+infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "+Infinity" Or trimmed_value equals "+INFINITY":
        Let result.is_valid be true
        Return result
    
    If trimmed_value equals "nan" Or trimmed_value equals "NaN" Or trimmed_value equals "NAN":
        Let result.is_valid be true
        Return result
    
    Note: Parse float components
    Let has_sign be false
    Let is_negative be false
    Let current_pos be 0
    
    Note: Check for sign
    If length of trimmed_value is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be character at position 0 in trimmed_value
        If first_char equals "+":
            Let has_sign be true
            Let current_pos be 1
        Otherwise If first_char equals "-":
            Let has_sign be true
            Let is_negative be true
            Let current_pos be 1
    
    Note: Parse integer part
    Let integer_part_digits be 0
    Let integer_part_start be current_pos
    Let found_decimal be false
    Let decimal_position be -1
    
    Note: Find decimal point and count integer digits
    Loop with i from current_pos to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
        Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
        If char equals ".":
            If found_decimal:
                Let result.error_code be "MULTIPLE_DECIMALS"
                Let result.error_message be "Multiple decimal points found"
                Return result
            Let found_decimal be true
            Let decimal_position be i
            Break
        Otherwise If char equals "e" Or char equals "E":
            Break
        Otherwise If char equals "0" Or char equals "1" Or char equals "2" Or char equals "3" Or char equals "4" Or char equals "5" Or char equals "6" Or char equals "7" Or char equals "8" Or char equals "9":
            Let integer_part_digits be integer_part_digits plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let result.error_code be "INVALID_CHARACTER"
            Let result.error_message be "Invalid character '" concatenated with char concatenated with "' in float"
            Return result
    
    Note: Parse fractional part if decimal point exists
    Let fractional_part_digits be 0
    Let scientific_notation_start be -1
    
    If found_decimal:
        Let current_pos be decimal_position plus 1
        
        Note: Count fractional digits
        Loop with i from current_pos to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
            Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
            If char equals "e" Or char equals "E":
                Let scientific_notation_start be i
                Break
            Otherwise If char equals "0" Or char equals "1" Or char equals "2" Or char equals "3" Or char equals "4" Or char equals "5" Or char equals "6" Or char equals "7" Or char equals "8" Or char equals "9":
                Let fractional_part_digits be fractional_part_digits plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Let result.error_code be "INVALID_CHARACTER"
                Let result.error_message be "Invalid character '" concatenated with char concatenated with "' in fractional part"
                Return result
    Otherwise:
        Note: Look for scientific notation without decimal point
        Loop with i from current_pos to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
            Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
            If char equals "e" Or char equals "E":
                Let scientific_notation_start be i
                Break
    
    Note: Parse scientific notation if present
    Let has_exponent be false
    Let exponent_value be 0
    
    If scientific_notation_start is greater than -1:
        Let has_exponent be true
        Let current_pos be scientific_notation_start plus 1
        
        Note: Check for exponent sign
        Let exponent_is_negative be false
        If current_pos is less than length of trimmed_value:
            Let exp_char be character at position current_pos in trimmed_value
            If exp_char equals "+":
                Let current_pos be current_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If exp_char equals "-":
                Let exponent_is_negative be true
                Let current_pos be current_pos plus 1
        
        Note: Parse exponent digits
        Let exponent_digits be 0
        Let exponent_value be 0
        
        Loop with i from current_pos to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
            Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
            If char equals "0" Or char equals "1" Or char equals "2" Or char equals "3" Or char equals "4" Or char equals "5" Or char equals "6" Or char equals "7" Or char equals "8" Or char equals "9":
                Let digit_val be 0
                If char equals "0":
                    Let digit_val be 0
                Otherwise If char equals "1":
                    Let digit_val be 1
                Otherwise If char equals "2":
                    Let digit_val be 2
                Otherwise If char equals "3":
                    Let digit_val be 3
                Otherwise If char equals "4":
                    Let digit_val be 4
                Otherwise If char equals "5":
                    Let digit_val be 5
                Otherwise If char equals "6":
                    Let digit_val be 6
                Otherwise If char equals "7":
                    Let digit_val be 7
                Otherwise If char equals "8":
                    Let digit_val be 8
                Otherwise If char equals "9":
                    Let digit_val be 9
                
                Let exponent_value be exponent_value multiplied by 10 plus digit_val
                Let exponent_digits be exponent_digits plus 1
                
                Note: Prevent exponent overflow
                If exponent_value is greater than 308:
                    Let result.error_code be "EXPONENT_TOO_LARGE"
                    Let result.error_message be "Exponent value too large"
                    Return result
            Otherwise:
                Let result.error_code be "INVALID_CHARACTER"
                Let result.error_message be "Invalid character '" concatenated with char concatenated with "' in exponent"
                Return result
        
        Note: Check that exponent has at least one digit
        If exponent_digits equals 0:
            Let result.error_code be "MISSING_EXPONENT"
            Let result.error_message be "Scientific notation requires exponent digits"
            Return result
        
        Note: Apply exponent sign
        If exponent_is_negative:
            Let exponent_value be 0 minus exponent_value
    
    Note: Validate we have at least some digits
    Let total_digits be integer_part_digits plus fractional_part_digits
    If total_digits equals 0:
        Let result.error_code be "NO_DIGITS"
        Let result.error_message be "No digits found in float value"
        Return result
    
    Note: Validate precision constraint
    If precision is not null:
        If total_digits is greater than precision:
            Let result.error_code be "PRECISION_EXCEEDED"
            Let result.error_message be "Total digits " concatenated with total_digits concatenated with " exceeds precision limit " concatenated with precision
            Let result.expected_value be "total digits <= " concatenated with precision
            Return result
    
    Note: Validate scale constraint
    If scale is not null:
        If fractional_part_digits is greater than scale:
            Let result.error_code be "SCALE_EXCEEDED"
            Let result.error_message be "Fractional digits " concatenated with fractional_part_digits concatenated with " exceeds scale limit " concatenated with scale
            Let result.expected_value be "fractional digits <= " concatenated with scale
            Return result
    
    Note: Additional validations for reasonable float values
    If has_exponent:
        If exponent_value is greater than 308:
            Let result.error_code be "VALUE_TOO_LARGE"
            Let result.error_message be "Float value too large (exponent > 308)"
            Return result
        
        If exponent_value is less than -308:
            Let result.error_code be "VALUE_TOO_SMALL"
            Let result.error_message be "Float value too small (exponent < -308)"
            Return result
    
    Note: Validation successful
    Let result.is_valid be true
    Return result

Process called "validate_boolean" that takes value as String, accepted_formats as Optional[List[String]] returns ValidationResult:
    Note: Validate string represents a valid boolean value
    Note: Accepted formats: true/false, yes/no, 1/0, on/off (default: all)
    Note: Case-insensitive validation with format flexibility
    
    Let result be ValidationResult with:
        is_valid as false
        error_code as null
        error_message as null
        field_name as null
        expected_value as null
        actual_value as value
    
    Note: Check for empty or null string
    If value equals "" Or value equals null:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value cannot be empty for boolean validation"
        Return result
    
    Note: Remove leading and trailing whitespace and convert to lowercase
    Let trimmed_value be value
    Let start_index be 0
    Let end_index be 0
    
    Note: Find first non-whitespace character
    Loop while start_index is less than length of trimmed_value:
        Let char be character at position start_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let start_index be start_index plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Find last non-whitespace character
    Let end_index be length of trimmed_value minus 1
    Loop while end_index is greater than start_index:
        Let char be character at position end_index in trimmed_value
        If char equals " " Or char equals "\t" Or char equals "\n" Or char equals "\r":
            Let end_index be end_index minus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Extract and normalize substring
    If start_index is greater than end_index:
        Let result.error_code be "EMPTY_VALUE"
        Let result.error_message be "Value contains only whitespace"
        Return result
    
    Let trimmed_value be substring of trimmed_value from start_index to end_index plus 1
    
    Note: Convert to lowercase for case-insensitive comparison
    Let lowercase_value be ""
    Loop with i from 0 to length of trimmed_value minus 1:
        Let char be character at position i in trimmed_value
        If char equals "A":
            Let lowercase_value be lowercase_value concatenated with "a"
        Otherwise If char equals "B":
            Let lowercase_value be lowercase_value concatenated with "b"
        Otherwise If char equals "C":
            Let lowercase_value be lowercase_value concatenated with "c"
        Otherwise If char equals "D":
            Let lowercase_value be lowercase_value concatenated with "d"
        Otherwise If char equals "E":
